These are called buckets.

Initially

0 -> empty
1 -> empty
2 -> empty
...
9 -> empty
Now insert
unordered_map<int,string> mp;

mp[25] = "Apple";

The computer asks:

"Which bucket should key 25 go into?"

It uses a hash function.

For integers, imagine a simple hash function (the real one is more sophisticated):

hash(key) = key % number_of_buckets

Since there are 10 buckets

25 % 10 = 5

So

Bucket 5

25 -> Apple

Now the table looks like

0
1
2
3
4
5 ---> (25, Apple)
6
7
8
9

Notice that it didn't search through every element. It jumped directly to bucket 5.

Insert another
mp[13] = "Banana";
13 % 10 = 3

Now

3 ---> (13, Banana)
5 ---> (25, Apple)
Another
mp[44] = "Orange";
44 % 10 = 4
4 ---> (44, Orange)
What if two keys get the same bucket?

Suppose

mp[35] = "Mango";
35 % 10 = 5

But bucket 5 already has

25 -> Apple

Now what?

This is called a collision.

Collision Handling

Most C++ implementations use separate chaining.

Bucket 5 becomes

Bucket 5

25 -> Apple
35 -> Mango

Internally it is something like

5

↓

(25,Apple)
      ↓
(35,Mango)

Each bucket stores a small linked list (or a similar node-based structure).

Another collision
mp[45] = "Pear";
45 % 10 = 5

Now

Bucket 5

25 Apple
35 Mango
45 Pear
Searching

Suppose

mp.find(35);

The computer does

hash(35)

↓

35 % 10 = 5

Immediately jumps to bucket 5

25 Apple
35 Mango
45 Pear

Looks only inside this bucket.

Found!

Notice it never checks buckets 0–4 or 6–9.

That's why it's so fast.

Why is it O(1)?

Imagine

1,000,000 elements

A map has to walk a balanced tree, taking about

log₂(1,000,000) ≈ 20

comparisons.

An unordered_map computes the hash and jumps directly to one bucket.

If the hash function spreads keys well, each bucket contains only a few elements, so the search is effectively constant time.

What if all keys collide?

Imagine every key hashes to bucket 5.

5

↓

1
↓

2
↓

3
↓

4
↓

5
↓

...

Now searching becomes

O(n)

This is the worst case.

Fortunately, the standard library uses high-quality hash functions and automatically resizes the table to make this unlikely.

Rehashing

Suppose you start with 10 buckets.

After many insertions

Bucket 5

25
35
45
55
65
75

Too crowded!

The unordered_map creates a larger table, for example with 20 buckets, and reinserts every element.

Now

25 % 20 = 5
35 % 20 = 15
45 % 20 = 5
55 % 20 = 15

The elements spread out:

Bucket 5
25
45

Bucket 15
35
55

This process is called rehashing. It keeps operations fast by reducing collisions.
